---
/**
 * /calculator — Spend-ROI calculator (May 2026 plan, Workstream C, sub-project C3).
 *
 * Editorial counter to a competitor that paywalls the same feature.
 * Ships free, transparent, with methodology visible above the fold of the
 * results. The calculator reads typed `earnRates` from L2 cards.json via
 * `getAllCards()` — no LLM, no live scraping (Charter §6).
 */
import BaseLayout from "~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import RewardsCalculator from "~/components/islands/RewardsCalculator";
import { getAllCards } from "~/lib/cardsData";
import { AED_PER_UNIT } from "~/components/islands/RewardsCalculator";

const cards = getAllCards();
const cardCount = cards.length;
const lastUpdated = new Date().toLocaleDateString("en-GB", {
  day: "numeric",
  month: "long",
  year: "numeric",
});
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Spend-ROI calculator — DubaiPoints"
  description="A free, transparent calculator: enter your monthly spend across seven categories and see which UAE credit card pays you back the most. AED-first, methodology visible, no email wall."
  fullWidth
>
  <article class="dp-article is-wide">
    <header class="dp-article-head">
      <p class="dp-article-eyebrow is-green">Tool · Calculator</p>
      <h1 class="dp-article-title">
        Which UAE card pays you back the most on <em>your</em> spend?
      </h1>
      <p class="dp-article-lede">
        Enter your monthly spend across seven categories. We rank every
        card on the site by AED-equivalent monthly reward at its
        published earn rate. Methodology is below the calculator, not
        behind an email wall.
      </p>
      <p class="dp-article-meta">
        <strong>{cardCount}</strong> cards ranked
        <span class="sep">·</span> Last updated {lastUpdated}
        <span class="sep">·</span>
        <a href="#methodology">Methodology</a>
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="dp-take">
      <p class="label">How to read this</p>
      <p>
        We do not promise these rewards. We show what each card's
        published earn rate works out to on the spend you enter, using
        the AED conversion benchmarks in the methodology section. Your
        actual redemption value will differ; rare sweet spots beat
        these rates, mass-market redemptions sit below them.
      </p>
    </div>

    <RewardsCalculator client:load cards={cards} />

    <section id="methodology" class="dp-article-section">
      <h2>Methodology</h2>

      <p>
        The calculator joins your stated monthly spend to each card's
        typed <code>earnRates</code> in our data file
        (<a href="https://github.com/dubaipoints1/property/blob/main/src/data/cards.json">cards.json</a>),
        category-by-category. The sliders cover seven categories so
        the calculator hits feature parity with the dimensions a UAE
        reader expects — dining, groceries, fuel, travel, online
        shopping, utilities and entertainment.
      </p>

      <h3>The per-card formula</h3>
      <p>
        Each card's monthly reward is the sum of seven products —
        spend in each category multiplied by that card's earn rate
        for the category. Categories the card does not bonus fall
        through to its base rate (<code>everythingElse</code>).
        Utilities and telecom bills always use the base rate; UAE
        cards rarely bonus this category, and we do not want to
        invent an earn rate that does not exist.
      </p>

      <h3>Why we ignore caps by default</h3>
      <p>
        We apply per-category caps only when the card declares them
        in typed form (<code>earnRates._caps</code>). Cards that
        publish caps in marketing prose but not in the schedule of
        charges get the benefit of the doubt; we surface the cap on
        the review page so you can read it before applying.
      </p>

      <h3>The AED conversion table</h3>
      <p>
        Each card earns in its own unit — AED cashback, Skywards
        Miles, FAB Rewards, Darna, and so on. To rank cards against
        each other we convert into AED equivalents using a single
        published table. Updating these rates updates both the
        ranking and this section.
      </p>

      <table class="dp-data-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Earn unit family</th>
            <th>AED per native unit</th>
            <th>Examples</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>AED cashback</td>
            <td class="num">{AED_PER_UNIT.aed_cashback.toFixed(2)}</td>
            <td>FAB Cashback, Mashreq Cashback, ENBD Cashback</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Airline miles</td>
            <td class="num">{AED_PER_UNIT.miles.toFixed(2)}</td>
            <td>Emirates Skywards, Etihad Guest, Qatar Avios</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Bank-proprietary points</td>
            <td class="num">{AED_PER_UNIT.bank_points.toFixed(2)}</td>
            <td>FAB Rewards, ENBD Plus Points, ADCB TouchPoints, U Points, Darna</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Hotel points</td>
            <td class="num">{AED_PER_UNIT.hotel_points.toFixed(3)}</td>
            <td>Marriott Bonvoy</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Unknown / no loyalty programme</td>
            <td class="num">{AED_PER_UNIT.unknown.toFixed(2)}</td>
            <td>Fallback — flagged on the result tile</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>
        <em>
          These are conservative benchmarks; your actual redemption
          value will differ. Skywards First-class sweet spots reach
          5–7 fils per Mile; mass-market economy redemptions sit at
          3 fils. See the <a href="/valuations/methodology/">AED
          valuations methodology</a> for the underlying work.
        </em>
      </p>

      <h3>Annual fee handling</h3>
      <p>
        The default view shows monthly reward AED and annual fee
        separately. Toggle the "show net of annual fee" checkbox to
        subtract the monthly fee accrual (<code>annualFee / 12</code>)
        from the reward and re-rank. A fee-free card with a modest
        earn rate often beats a premium card once the fee lands.
      </p>

      <h3>Verification dates</h3>
      <p>
        Every ranked card carries its <code>lastVerified</code> date.
        Cards verified more than 90 days ago get a "data drift risk"
        chip — we do not hide them, but we tell you the figures may
        have moved.
      </p>

      <h3>What this calculator does not do</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          We do not score welcome bonuses. A card's first-year value
          can dwarf its earn rate; check the review page.
        </li>
        <li>
          We do not factor in lounge access, cinema BOGO, golf, the
          Entertainer, or hotel discounts. Use the
          <a href="/cards/">cards directory</a> filters for those.
        </li>
        <li>
          We do not check your eligibility. Each result tile links
          to the full card review with salary band and salary-transfer
          requirements.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <footer class="dp-article-foot">
      <p>
        Found a card whose earn rate looks wrong? Email
        <strong>corrections@dubaipoints.ae</strong> or open an issue
        on the data file. Every fix gets attributed on our
        <a href="/corrections/">corrections page</a>.
      </p>
    </footer>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
